/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (The illicium of the humpback anglerfish supports a bioluminescent esca whose flash patterns) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (have long been assumed to be constant. Using a pressure-tolerant low-light camera array) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (deployed at 1,150 metres in the Cayman Trough, we recorded 41 hours of undisturbed lure) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (behaviour across nine individuals. We report that escal flashes are not constant but follow) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (three reproducible temporal regimes that correlate with the proximity of mobile prey. We) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (argue that lure timing is an actively modulated hunting behaviour rather than a passive) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm (metabolic by-product of the symbiotic bacteria that produce the light.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 546.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (Bioluminescence in the deep sea is overwhelmingly a story of chemistry borrowed from) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (microbes. In the humpback anglerfish, the light organ at the tip of the dorsal lure, or) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (esca, houses a dense colony of symbiotic bacteria of the genus Enterovibrio. Because the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm (fish cannot synthesise luciferin on its own, the prevailing twentieth-century view held that) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (the glow was effectively always on, a steady beacon dictated by bacterial metabolism rather) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm (than by the host.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm (That view sits awkwardly beside the energetics of the abyss. Prey encounters below a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 402.0 Tm (kilometre are rare, and an indiscriminately glowing lure is as likely to attract a larger) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 388.0 Tm (predator as a meal. We hypothesised that the anglerfish exercises far more control over its) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 374.0 Tm (lure than the passive model allows, and that this control would be visible as structured) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 360.0 Tm (timing rather than constant illumination.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 346.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm (Field Methods) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm (Observations were made during three dives of the submersible tender Cyana II over the Cayman) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm (Trough between March and May of the study year. A baited but unlit camera platform was) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (lowered to 1,150 metres and left to acclimate for ninety minutes before recording,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm (minimising disturbance from the descent lights. Imaging used an intensified sensor sensitive) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 258.0 Tm (to the 470-490 nanometre band characteristic of escal emission, with no supplemental) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 244.0 Tm (illumination during recording.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 230.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 216.0 Tm (We scored each flash event for duration, peak relative intensity, and inter-flash interval.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 202.0 Tm (Prey proximity was estimated from the same footage by tracking the silhouettes of mobile) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 188.0 Tm (zooplankton and small crustaceans against the faint downwelling background. Nine individual) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 174.0 Tm (anglerfish were identified by the unique branching pattern of their escal appendages and) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 160.0 Tm (tracked across the recording window.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 146.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (Three Flash Regimes) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm (The footage resolved into three statistically distinct regimes. In the quiescent regime,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 100.0 Tm (observed when no prey was within roughly two body lengths, the esca produced long, dim,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 86.0 Tm (widely spaced flashes averaging one event every 38 seconds. This is the closest the animal) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 72.0 Tm (came to the textbook 'constant beacon', yet even here the light was clearly pulsed rather) Tj
